EventType.Explanation: A parse error indicates a malformed XML document; for example, a document that contains an illegal character, mismatched element end-tags or trailing content after the document element. Examine the specific error message and correct the XML document.

An out of memory error indicates memory depletion while parsing of an XML document. Memory depletion can result from an excessively large document, a main document that includes large amounts of external data, or explosive entity expansion.

The XML parser has user configurable limits on various characteristics of an XML document, to include document size, element nesting depth and the number of attributes on a single element. This error indicates that a document has exceeded one of those limits and has been rejected. If document rejection is the desired behavior, no action is required; if the document should not have been rejected, correct the problem by reconfiguring the limits to accept the rejected document.

An XML Firewall service has rejected a SOAP message because the message contained a DTD (Document Type Declaration). Such messages are not allowed by the SOAP standard. Correct the problem by removing the DTD from the XML document or by reconfiguring the XML Firewall service to a non-soap parsing mode, such as "xml" or "unprocessed".

EventType.Description: Processing instruction encountered in SOAP context
EventType.Explanation: An XML Firewall service has rejected a SOAP message because the message contained a PI (Processing Instruction). Such messages are not allowed by the SOAP standard. Correct the problem by removing the processing instruction from the XML document or by reconfiguring the XML Firewall service to a non-soap parsing mode, such as "xml" or "unprocessed".

This error indicates that an external service has interrupted the parser and ordered it to abort, though no XML parse error may have occurred. This can happen, for example, if a network service such an XML Firewall has to close a connection and there is no need to finish a parse in a process. Examine the other log messages surrounding this one to determine the root cause of the problem.
An internal error occurred in the parser; contact DataPower for support.

The XML parser has a user configurable limit on the maximum size of any single node in an XML document. This error indicates that a node in a document has exceeded this limit and has been rejected. If document rejection is the desired behavior, no action is required; if the document should have been rejected, correct the problem by increasing the maximum node size allowed on the XML manager associated with this service.

EventType.Description: Forbidden external reference encountered while parsing XML. External DTD/entity references are no longer allowed by default.
EventType.Explanation: The XML parser has a user configurable toggle that determines if the xml parser will retrieve external documents to resolve external DTD or external entity reference in the input document. This error indicates that an external reference has been encountered in an input document when the parser has been configured to reject such references. If document rejection is the desired behavior, no action is required; if the document should not have been rejected, correct the problem by enabling external references on the XML manager associated with this service.

EventType.Description: Out of memory due to max-node-size too small
EventType.Explanation: The XML parser has run out of memory while parsing an XML document due to the value of the max-node-size parser limit. Try returning the max-node-size parser limit on the appropriate XML Manager or Service object to the default 32MB.

A read error indicates an I/O error in the data stream the XML document handler is reading from, for example a reset connection, a network protocol error, etc. Examine other log messages surrounding this one to determine the root cause of the problem.

A connect error indicates an error that prevented the establishment of a connection between the DataPower device and the source of an XML document, for example an invalid URL, a refused connection, etc. Examine other log messages surrounding this one to determine the root cause of the problem.

A dynamic execution error indicates some sort of illegal xslt operation occurred. An example would be calling a template that does not exist, or misusing a variable's value (such as an illegal use of a number as a nodeset). Examine the error logs and repair the stylesheet.

A static compilation error indicates that a stylesheet could not be prepared for execution because it is invalid according to the XSLT specification. For example, if a stylesheet contained typos in the name of an XSLT command and as a result had an illegal element name, it would be a static error because the stylesheet could not be executed. Examine the stylesheet error log and repair the stylesheet.
See message text.

An error has occurred on output. This indicates that the network connection has failed or some other output error. The execution of the stylesheet has been terminated. Examine the error logs to find more details.
Verify that the file exists.

EventType.Description: Access Denied - use 'cancel' to exit any submode.
EventType.Explanation: The RBM policy of the user denies access to the attempted operation. Check the RBM policy for the users permissions. If you have entered a configuration submode, you will have to use 'cancel' to exit.
This result indicates that the memory of the device has been exhausted. In this unlikely event the device will be restarted automatically to clear the condition. No user intervention is required.

This result indicates an attempt to change or create configuration using an invalid type of configuration object. The most likely cause is a typo in the cli command and can be corrected by verifying the command syntax.

The most likely cause is a typo in the cli command and can be corrected by changing the name or verifying that the intended configuration object exists.

This message indicates an attempt to reference a non-existing configuration object. The most likely cause is a typo in the cli command. Verify the existence of the intended configuration object through the 'show' command or web-mgmt.

This message indicates an attempt to remove a configuration object which is referenced by another configuration object. Verify the configuration dependency chain through the web-mgmt and remove the configuration from the top down.
This result indicates a failure to install the XML Management Interface. The most likely cause is an invalid port. Verify the XML Management Interface configuration.
This result indicates an invalid number of configuration parameters. The most likely cause is a typo in the CLI command. Verify the CLI syntax by using '?'.

This result indicates the failed attempt to allocate a custom log category. Another custom log category of the same name already exists in the system. Custom log categories have to be unique on a system basis. Change the name of the log category.

EventType.Description: PKCS7-SMIME is not licensed for this device

An internal error has occurred. Contact DataPower support.

EventType.Description: INPUT not available or cannot be used this way
EventType.Explanation: The INPUT context is being used by the configuration, but it is not available. This message usually indicates that multistep processing rule was invoked with the "Non-XML Processing" switch on in some context where it is executed for side effects only.
An external URL being accessed via a results or fetch action could not be accessed due to a DNS resolution failure .
An external URL being accessed via a results or fetch action could not be accessed due to a service unreachable error.
An external URL being accessed via a results or fetch action could not be accessed due to a network time limit being exceeded.
An external URL being accessed via a resuls or fetch action could not be accessed due to a protocol response failure.
An external URL access could not be completed due to an unexpected network error.
A stylesheet configured with streaming input required was not available, or compiled in non-streaming mode.
The CALL rule stack limit has been exceeded. Check for a unintended loop or increase the value of var://service/max-call-depth. The default is 128 and it must be in the range of 2 - 2048.
The CALL action references a rule which is not operational. The rule could be disabled or has encountered a runtime error. Check the runtime state of the rule referenced by the CALL action.

EventType.Description: Binary stylesheet is incompatible with non-binary processing action
EventType.Explanation: The processing action is of a non-binary type (i.e., it is not XFORMBIN or CRYPTOBIN), but it references a binary stylesheet containing DataGlue instructions. Change the action type or change the stylesheet.

EventType.Description: Multiple attachment packages were written to the output context
EventType.Explanation: Multiple contexts containing attachment packages were written to the output context, either directly or through a results action. It is illegal to have multiple end boundaries in the message. Use the fetch action or a custom stylesheet to combine the packages in one context.

EventType.Description: Root part not first in streaming conformance mode
EventType.Explanation: When the attachment processing mode is set to streaming and Attachment Profile conformance checking is on, the root part must be the first part of the message

EventType.Description: Loop/conditional action recursive depth too deep
EventType.Explanation: A conditional or for-each action was set as its own target action, possibly indirectly.

A conditional, for-each, or event-sink action referenced an action that does not exist. Repair the name of the action referenced by the conditional, for-each, or event-sink action, or create an action with the correct name.
An event-sink action is specified as waiting on an action that is not asynchronous.

The specified timeout expired while waiting for an event-sink action's target actions to finish. Increase the timeout if necessary. This error may also occur if an event-sink is specified to wait for a valid action that is not actually invoked.
The runtime error is thrown when transforming an dpa request.
The convert-http action was called from a rule that does not have a URL; for example in a scheduled rule.
The input message should have been signed with smime 3.1 either using an enveloped signature or as a multipart/signed message.
The JSON parser was unable to parse the message as JSON.
An error occurred, but was handled by an "on error" rule within multistep.

EventType.Description: Message is not a SOAP 1.1 or 1.2 document
EventType.Explanation: The message sent by the client was not a valid SOAP message, and the firewall has been configured to require SOAP messages. If non-SOAP messages are to be accepted, modify the firewall to allow "raw XML" and verify that all processing rules have been modified to no longer assume SOAP messages.

While the message sent by the client had a top-level SOAP element, it failed to validate against the appropriate schema (version 1.1 or 1.2). If it is not feasible to inspect the message at the client side, use the packet capture facility to save a copy of the erroneous message and determine what needs to be corrected in the client application.

EventType.Description: Rejected by filter; SOAP fault sent
EventType.Explanation: A filtering rule invoked by the firewall rejected the message. Any details will appear in the SOAP fault that is returned to the client application. It's likely that no further action is necessary.

EventType.Description: Rejected by filter; error reply sent
EventType.Explanation: A filtering rule invoked by the firewall rejected the message. Any details will appear in the custom error message sent back by the filter. It's likely that no further action is necessary.
The message, in terms of the number of bytes sent over the network, was too large. If necessary, change the firewall configuration to increase the maximum message size, or set it to unlimited.
The user has specified a schema against which to validate the SOAP message body; either the SOAP envelope is invalid or the SOAP body failed to validate.
Message violates the configured policy.
The DNS (Domain Name System) could not locate the IP address of the configured NTP server. Verify the existence of the specified server.
An invalid IP address (probably to localhost) was configured as the NTP server. Verify the NTP server address.
The NTP update failed due to lack of internal system resources. This error should be temporary.
The NTP update failed due to an internal resource conflict. This error should be temporary.
The NTP update failed due to a network error at request generation time. Perhaps there is no route to the NTP server or the required interface is down.
The NTP update received an error trying to read the response from the NTP server. There was probably an error on the assoicated network interface.
The NTP update was aborted because a response was received from a rogue NTP server.
The NTP update was aborted because the NTP server did not respond within 750ms of the NTP request generation.
The NTP service is not operational because no servers are configured.
The name of the file associated with this Crypto object is illegal. Check that the name corresponds to an actual readable file.
The file associated with this Crypto object is not readable. Check that the file exists and has permissions allowing it to be read.

EventType.Description: File is not in a known format
EventType.Explanation: The file associated with this Crypto object is not in a format which the device understands. Crypto Key files in the following formats are acceptable: DER, PEM, PKCS#12, and PKCS#8. Crypto Certificate files in the following formats are acceptable: DER, PEM, PKCS#12, and PKCS#7.
There was an error reading the file containing this Crypto Shared Secret Key. The file may be corrupted or empty. Try uploading the file to the device again.
The NotBefore field in this Crypto Certificate is invalid. This may indicate the certificate file was generated improperly or is corrupted.

The NotBefore field in this Crypto Certificate indicates this certificate is not yet usable. Examining the certificate will show the date and time when this certificate becomes usable. If you think the certificate should be usable, ensure that the system time on the device is correct and/or that NTP is enabled. Remember to account for time zone differences.
The NotAfter field in this Crypto Certificate is invalid. This may indicate the certificate file was generated improperly or is corrupted.

The NotAfter field in this Crypto Certificate indicates this certificate is expired and is no longer usable. Examining the certificate will show the date and time when this certificate expires. If you think the certificate should still be usable, ensure that the system time on the device is correct and/or that NTP is enabled. Remember to account for time zone differences.

The private key in the Crypto Key object, and the public key contained in the Crypto Certificate object for this Identification Credential do not form a valid public/private key pair. Check that the correct key and certificate objects are configured, and that those objects in turn are associated with the correct files.

EventType.Description: No keys, sskeys, or certificates specified
EventType.Explanation: This Firewall Credentials object does not contain any Crypto Certificate, Crypto Key, or Crypto Shared Secret Key objects. You must configure one or more certificate, key, or sskey objects as part of this Firewall Credentials object.
The type of this SSLProxyProfile is not a known type. It should be one of: forward, reverse, or two-way
There was a problem initializing this SSLProxy Profile. Examine the log for more specific error information.
There was a problem with the pkcs12 file. It does not contain a private key. Examine the log for more specific error information.

EventType.Description: Unable to make a valid certificate from input file
EventType.Explanation: System is not able to retrieve a valid certificate from the input file, maybe the file is not good or system does not support this certificate, contact with the manufacturer.
Every multistep rule must have at least one action. Configure one or more rules with the WebGUI or CLI.

EventType.Description: Malformed PIPEline: first action reads from PIPE
EventType.Explanation: The input to the first action in this multistep rule reads from the special 'PIPE' context. PIPE is a special context that allows the output of one action to be used as the input of the next without any intermediate storage; as such, it does not make sense to have an action with a PIPE input that is not preceded by an action with a PIPE output. Modify the configuration to read from a different context, for example INPUT.

EventType.Description: Malformed PIPEline: PIPE input not preceded by PIPE output
EventType.Explanation: The input to an action is a PIPE, but the previous action does not output to PIPE. PIPE is a special context that allows the output of one action to be used as the input of the next without any intermediate storage; as such, it does not make sense to have an action with a PIPE input that is not preceded by an action with a PIPE output. Modify the configuration to read from a different context.

EventType.Description: Malformed PIPEline: PIPE output not followed by PIPE input
EventType.Explanation: The output of an action is a PIPE, but the next action does not read from PIPE. PIPE is a special context that allows the output of one action to be used as the input of the next without any intermediate storage; as such, it does not make sense to have an action with a PIPE output that is not followed by an action with a PIPE input. Modify the configuration to write to a different context.

EventType.Description: Malformed PIPEline: last action outputs to PIPE
EventType.Explanation: The output of the last action is a PIPE. PIPE is a special context that allows the output of one action to be used as the input of the next without any intermediate storage; as such, it does not make sense to have an action with a PIPE output that is not followed by an action with a PIPE input. Modify the configuration to write to a different context, for example OUTPUT.
A multistep rule while processing its configuration found an uninitialized action. The system will correct this condition. It is not a serious error.
The HTTP request was of version 0.9. A minimum level of 1.0 is required.
Strict proxies require an HTTP host header for routing. No host header was found.
The HTTP request headers for this transaction did not conform to RFC 2616 and could not be parsed.
A rate limit cap imposed by the message monitoring subsystem was exceeded and enforcement of this policy forced the transaction to be rejected.

EventType.Description: Failed to establish a backside connection
EventType.Explanation: A dynamic routing failure has occurred. The backend host was successfully selected, but a network connection to it could not be established.
No network connection between the device and the backside server could be established.
A connection was established with the backside server, but that server disconnected unexpectedly during the transaction.
A dynamic firewall was configured, but no routing target was specified for this transaction. Specify routing target with a route step or via the xset-target extension function.

EventType.Description: Dynamic target specified unknown SSL proxy
EventType.Explanation: A dynamic route required the use of SSL and a specific proxy profile for the backside conneciton. The required proxy profile was not configured on the device.

EventType.Description: Dynamic target specified invalid SSL proxy
EventType.Explanation: The configured dynamic route required use of SSL. However no dynamic proxy profile was specified on this transaction, and there is no default SSL proxy profile associated with this proxy that is active.
URL violated syntax requirements and could not be created.
The HTTP response headers received from the backside server for this transaction did not conform to RFC 2616 and could not be parsed.

EventType.Description: Malformed version headers for HTTP request
EventType.Explanation: The HTTP request did not provide a version string (e.g. HTTP/1.0 or HTTP/1.1) understood by the device as specified by RFC 2616.

EventType.Description: Malformed method headers for HTTP request
EventType.Explanation: The HTTP request method did not conform to one specified by RFC 2616 or was prohibited by configuration. It should most likely have been POST.

EventType.Description: Malformed version headers for HTTP response
EventType.Explanation: The HTTP response did not begin with a recognizable version string as specified by RFC 2616. An example would be HTTP/1.1 200 Transaction OK.
The HTTP request header exceeded a size restriction. Either the header was more than 128KB or the URL being requested exceeded 16KB.
The HTTP response header exceeded 128KB.

EventType.Description: Connection terminated before request headers read because of the connection error occurs
EventType.Explanation: The HTTP client terminated the TCP session before sending a complete set of HTTP request headers. One cause of this error is not using SSL to connect to a port which is expecting SSL. For example, trying to connect to the WebGUI and mistyping "http://mydevice:9090" instead of "https://mydevice:9090" (assuming "mydevice" is your DataPower device and it's configured to listen on port 9090 for WebGUI connections).

EventType.Description: Connection terminated before response headers read because of the connection error occurs
EventType.Explanation: The back side server terminated the TCP session before sending a complete set of HTTP response headers.
The HTTP request headers received from the front side client for this transaction did not conform to RFC 2616 and could not be parsed.
The HTTP response headers received from the backside server for this transaction did not conform to RFC 2616 and could not be parsed.
An unexepected network hangup has occurred, forcing the cancellation of this transaction.
An object is not sufficiently configred
The backside URL was not well formed.
No host header was in the received request. All HTTP/1.1 level requests require a host header according to RFC 2616.
An expect request header was received that was unknown to the gateway.
A document was submitted to the gateway without any method of determining its length.
Processing of the HTTP Via header has detected a gateway loop and therefore the processing was aborted.

EventType.Description: Request did not match allowed-feature list
EventType.Explanation: The allowed-features attribute was used to specify as mask of required HTTP versions or methods on incoming requests. The incoming request did not meet those criteria.
Gateway's that contain at least one XTC front side protocol handler may only be dynamically routed.
The query string length parameter of the front side protocol handler was set to a value smaller than the length of the actual querystring received.
Too many HTTP headers were detected compared to the allowed configuration.
The length of a header value exceeded the configured allowable size.
The length of a header name exceeded the configured allowable size.
The request contained two or more content-length headers. This is usually an attempt to subvert the firewall and silently tunnel a request through.

The request was of a type that should not contain a body (get or head) but a content-length header greater than zero was present. This is often an attempt to subvert the firewall and pass a message through undeteceted.

EventType.Description: Request was both length and chunked delimited
EventType.Explanation: The request contained a body that was delimited both by a content-length and a transfer-encoding header. This is an illegal combination and might be an attempt to subvert a bug in the Apache 2.0.45 webserver.
A multiprotocol gateway must have at least one source protocol handler configured on it.

EventType.Description: AAA required to open WS-Addressing Channel
EventType.Explanation: The property to require AAA processing before trusting AAA input is set to true, and a new channel could not be created because this pre-requisite has not been satisified. This is a security consideration of whether untrusted message submissions should allow the appliance to create outbound TCP connections.

You were attempting to do an operation that required a two way exchange pattern, but only one direction was submitted. Gatewaying an asynchronous WS-Addressing front side to a one way backside is a common cause of this error.
The transaction has attempted to create an asynchronous backside reply addressed back to the appliance. However, no WS-Addressing Reply Point has been configured.
A WSA-Addressing reply was expected to arrive on a new channel, but that did not happen successfuly.

A WSA-Addressing replyto header could not be written because the contents of var://context/__WSA_REQUEST/replyto were empty. This variable must contain the value fo the reply-to annotation to be added to the outgoing asynchronous message. This variable is only required in the out-of-band message generation style, though it will be honored in the asynchronous style as well.
An asynchronous ws-addressing reply was expected, but not received in time.
The WS-Addressing Asynchrnous reply message could not be saved for later processing due to a conflict with an existing message ID. Each message must have its own unique identifier.

EventType.Description: HTTP/1.0 Get attempted with flow control enabled
EventType.Explanation: HTTP/1.0 Get is not supported with flow control enabled. Either upgrade the request to HTTP/1.1 GET or disable flow control.
Flow Control was enabled, however properties 'Stream Output to Front' and 'Stream Output to Back' must be set to 'Stream Messages.'

EventType.Description: HTTP request with Content-Type multipart/form-data attempted with flow control enabled
EventType.Explanation: Content-Type multipart/form-data is not supported with flow control enabled.

EventType.Description: Flow control enabled without Pass-through or Non-XML
EventType.Explanation: Flow Control was enabled. However, the 'Response-Type' and 'Request-Type' properties must be set to 'Pass through' or 'Non-XML'.

EventType.Description: Flow control enabled without chunked uploads
EventType.Explanation: Flow Control was enabled, however property 'Allow Chunked Uploads' must be set to 'On'.

EventType.Description: Connection terminated and no response headers read because of the server terminated the connection
EventType.Explanation: The back side server terminated the TCP session before sending a complete set of HTTP request headers.
An unexpected network hangup has occurred, forcing the cancellation of this transaction.
The connection timed out, forcing the cancellation of this transaction.

EventType.Description: The HTTP header is not terminated.
EventType.Explanation: The HTTP header is not terminated.

EventType.Description: The URI field in HTTP header is missing
EventType.Explanation: The URI field in the HTTP header is missing.

EventType.Description: The Version field in HTTP header is missing
EventType.Explanation: The version field in HTTP header is missing.
The Version field in HTTP header is invalid.

EventType.Description: The Host field in HTTP header is missing
EventType.Explanation: The Host field in HTTP header is missing.
Transfer-Encoding is only for HTTP/1.1

EventType.Description: The order of 'chunked, gzip' is illegal
EventType.Explanation: The order of "gzip, chunked" is legal but not "chunked, gzip"
The Content-Length is required

EventType.Description: Connection hangup when processing the incoming header
EventType.Explanation: An unexepected network hangup has occurred when processing the incoming header, forcing the cancellation of this transaction.
A network connection error has occurred.
A format error has occurred when processing the incoming data.

EventType.Description: Error occurs when initializing the stream
EventType.Explanation: An error occurs when initializing the stream.
Internal stream error.

EventType.Description: Cannot allocate enough memory for the incoming data
EventType.Explanation: No enough memory for the incoming data.
Errors when transcoding the data.
Read the data error.
Write the data error.
The request was not gatewayed or proxied because it was handled internally, as with a TRACE or OPTIONS transaction.
XML Firewal Local configuration changed.
The device ran out of memory resources when attempting to convert between encodings.
The UTF-8 text could not be read in because it contained an invalid UTF-8 character. Verify that the input text is actually UTF-8 encoded.
The UTF-16 text could not be read in because it contained an invalid UTF-16 character. Verify that the input text is actually UTF-16 encoded.

The EBCDIC text could not be read in because it contained an invalid EBCDIC character. Verify that the input text is actually EBCDIC encoded. It is also possible that the text is encoded in an unsupported EBCDIC variant.

EventType.Description: Attempted to encode a character which cannot be represented in Latin-1
EventType.Explanation: The text could not be encoded in Latin-1 because it contained symbols that Latin-1 cannot represent. Latin-1 can only represent U+000 to U+255.

EventType.Description: Attempted to encode a character which cannot be represented in Latin-2
EventType.Explanation: The text could not be encoded in Latin-2 because it contained symbols that Latin-1 cannot represent. Latin-2 can only represent U+000 to U+255.

EventType.Description: Attempted to encode a character which cannot be represented in EBCDIC
EventType.Explanation: The text could not be encoded in EBCDIC because it contained symbols that EBCDIC cannot represent. EBCDIC supports only a narrow range of characters.
An unknown character set encoding name was provided.

The text could not be converted from one character set to another because it was not valid according to its input encoding. Check that the input encoding in the XML file or binary-data description is correct. For example, the non-breaking space character U+00A0 would be represented by the single byte 0xA0 in the ISO-8859-1 encoding, but that byte is not a valid UTF-8 encoding of anything.

EventType.Description: Invalid character for output text encoding
EventType.Explanation: The text could not be converted from one character set to another because it contained a character that can not be represented in the output encoding. For example, the Greek lowercase "alpha" character U+0381 cannot be represented in the ISO-8859-1 encoding, which only supports characters U+0000 through U+00FF. Consider an encoding such as UTF-8 or UTF-16 that supports all Unicode characters.

EventType.Description: Could not send, message is too large (Reason Code 2010)
EventType.Explanation: The destination could not accept the message. (Reason Code 2010) Most likely there is an configuration error with the MQ QM maximum message size.
MQ encountered a temporary non-specific resource allocation error during message processing.
The MQ proxy lost the connection to the queue manager on the backend. Verify the communications channels on both devices.
The MQ proxy encountered a non-specific multistep error during message processing. Examine the multistep error log for more details on the failure.
The MQ proxy encountered a non-specific multistep error during message processing. Examine the multistep error log for more details on the failure.
The MQ proxy encountered an error sending the request to the backend queue manager. Verify the configuration as well as queue manager availability.
The MQ proxy encountered an error getting a response from the backend queue manager. Verify the configuration as well as queue manager availability.

EventType.Description: could not connect to the back QM
EventType.Explanation: The MQ proxy either could not open a connection to the backend queue manager or could not open the queues on the backend queue manager. Verify the proxy configuration as well as queue manager availability.

EventType.Description: could not enable listener (client port not set)
EventType.Explanation: The MQ gateway could not be enabled. A client port is not configured. Verify the configuration.
The MQ gateway could be enabled because the server's listener could not be enabled. Verify the configuration.
A limit imposed by the message monitors was exceeded and enforcement of this policy forced the transaction to be dropped.
There was some nonrecoverable error with the QM which forced it to be taken down.

EventType.Description: The unit-of-work was backed out (Reason Code 2003)
EventType.Explanation: The commit operation failed. (Reason Code 2003)
The connection to the QM was broken. (Reason Code 2009) This is probably due to the MQ QM server going down or a network problem.

EventType.Description: MQGET is not allowed on this queue (Reason Code 2016)
EventType.Explanation: MQGET is inhibited for the queue. (Reason Code 2016) Check the queue name or the permissions on the MQ QM server.

EventType.Description: The get or put call failed due to QM transactionality limit (Reason Code 2024)
EventType.Explanation: The MQ QM maximum uncommitted messages limit has been reached. (Reason Code 2024) Either the application is looping or the limits on the MQ QM are too low.

EventType.Description: A new connection could not be opened (Reason Code 2025)
EventType.Explanation: The MQ QM maximum concurrent connections limit has been reached. (Reason Code 2025) Either adjust the limit on the MQ QM object or on the server.

EventType.Description: The message could not be put on the queue (Reason Code 2030)
EventType.Explanation: The message could not be put since it exceeds the size for the queue or QM. (Reason Code 2030) Either adjust the limit on the MQ QM object or on the server.

EventType.Description: The get call timed out before receiving any messages (Reason Code 2033)
EventType.Explanation: The get call timed out before the backend could reply. (Reason Code 2033)

EventType.Description: The call failed due to permissions for this user (Reason Code 2035)
EventType.Explanation: The call failed for the specific user. (Reason Code 2035) Make sure that the MQ QM user parameter is set correctly and that the alternate user authority toggle is also correct.

EventType.Description: The call failed because the queue is in use (Reason Code 2042)
EventType.Explanation: The MQOPEN call failed. (Reason Code 2042) Either the queue is not sharable and was opened or the open options conflict with a previous open call.

EventType.Description: The call failed because the options for this call are invalid (Reason Code 2045)
EventType.Explanation: The MQOPEN or MQCLOSE call failed. (Reason Code 2045) The options are not valid for that type of queue. Check the call options and the queue definition.

EventType.Description: Could not send, message priority is too high (Reason Code 2049)
EventType.Explanation: The destination could not accept the message. (Reason Code 2049) Most likely there is an configuration error with MQMD.Priority field value.

EventType.Description: Could not send, MQPUT is not allowed (Reason Code 2051)
EventType.Explanation: The destination queue cannot be opened for put. (Reason Code 2051) Check the queue name or the permissions on the MQ QM server.

EventType.Description: Could not send, destination queue is full (Reason Code 2053)
EventType.Explanation: The destination queue is full. (Reason Code 2053) Most likely there is an error with the backend service reading from the queue.

EventType.Description: Could not send due to lack of storage (Reason Code 2056)
EventType.Explanation: The destination queue or QM does not have available storage. (Reason Code 2056) Check the disk usage on the MQ QM server.

EventType.Description: Could not connect to the named QM (Reason Code 2058)
EventType.Explanation: The QM name is not valid or not known. (Reason Code 2058) Check the queue manager name in the configuration.

EventType.Description: Could not connect to the QM (Reason Code 2059)
EventType.Explanation: The QM is not available. (Reason Code 2059) Check the queue manager host and port and total connection limit in the configuration.

EventType.Description: Could not get, truncated messages not accepted (Reason Code 2080)
EventType.Explanation: The message was to large for the available buffer and the device will not accept truncated messages. (Reason Code 2080) Check to make sure the maximum message size is sufficient.

EventType.Description: Could not open the alias Q (Reason Code 2082)
EventType.Explanation: The alias queue does not have a valid base queue name. (Reason Code 2082) Check the Base Queue Name parameter is the alias queue definition.

EventType.Description: Could not open, destination queue or topic object is unknown (Reason Code 2085)
EventType.Explanation: The destination queue or topic object is unknown. (Reason Code 2085) Most likely there is an configuration error with the queue or topic object.

EventType.Description: Could not open, remote queue manager is unknown (Reason Code 2087)
EventType.Explanation: The remote queue manager is unknown. (Reason Code 2087)

EventType.Description: Could not convert the message (Reason Code 2110)
EventType.Explanation: The message format does not allow conversion. (Reason Code 2110) Disable the MQ QM 'Convert Input' parameter to get the message.

EventType.Description: Operation failed due to quiescing QM (Reason Code 2161)
EventType.Explanation: The QM is shutting down. (Reason Code 2161)

EventType.Description: Operation failed due to stopping QM (Reason Code 2162)
EventType.Explanation: The QM is shutting down. (Reason Code 2162)

EventType.Description: Message was too big for the channel (Reason Code 2218)
EventType.Explanation: The message sent to a remote queue was too big for the channel. (Reason Code 2218)
The message has been reprocessed too many times. (Reason Code 2362)

EventType.Description: MQPUT call failed since segments are not supported (Reason Code 2365)
EventType.Explanation: The queue cannot accept segmented messages. (Reason Code 2365)

EventType.Description: SSL connection cannot be established (Reason Code 2371)
EventType.Explanation: The SSL key-exchange or authentication failed. (Reason Code 2371)

EventType.Description: SSL initialization failed due to a key repository error (Reason Code 2381)
EventType.Explanation: The database could not be found or could not be opened. (Reason Code 2381) Check the filename and directory location; make sure the password stash file exists in the same location and that the password has not expired.

EventType.Description: SSL has already been initialized (Reason Code 2391)
EventType.Explanation: The SSL connection is already active. (Reason Code 2391)

EventType.Description: SSL configuration is not valid (Reason Code 2392)
EventType.Explanation: The SSL configuration is not valid. (Reason Code 2392)
The SSL initialization could not complete. (Reason Code 2393)

EventType.Description: SSL cipher suite not known (Reason Code 2400)
EventType.Explanation: The SSL cipher suite is unknown. (Reason Code 2400)

EventType.Description: SSL certificate has been revoked (Reason Code 2401)
EventType.Explanation: The SSL certificate is not valid. (Reason Code 2401)
The SSL certificate store is not valid. (Reason Code 2402)

EventType.Description: SSL Key Repository conversion to SSL Proxy Profile failed

EventType.Explanation: The get call that tried to retrieve or browse the message under cursor but failed due to no message under cursor. (Reason Code 2034)
An MQOPEN, or MQSUB call was issued but a selection string was specified which contained a syntax error. (Reason Code 2459)

EventType.Description: MQSUB calls are currently inhibited for the topic subscribed to. (Reason Code 2503)
EventType.Explanation: MQSUB calls are currently inhibited for the topic subscribed to. (Reason Code 2503)

EventType.Description: Invalid topic string is specified. (Reason Code 2425)
EventType.Explanation: On the MQSUB call in the Subscription Descriptor MQSD the resultant full topic string is not valid. (Reason Code 2425)

EventType.Description: The topic of the subscriptions cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2510)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call using option MQSO_ALTER was made changing the topic of the subscription. The topic of a subscription cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2510)

EventType.Description: The sublevel of the subscriptions cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2512)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call using option MQSO_ALTER was made changing the SubLevel of the subscription. The SubLevel of a subscription cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2512)

EventType.Description: The named subscription is in used by another application. (Reason Code 2429)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call using option MQSO_RESUME was made specifying a full subscription name that exists and is in use by another application. (Reason Code 2429)

EventType.Description: The subscription named in the MQSUB call is invalid. (Reason Code 2523)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call using MQSO_RESUME or MQSO_ALTER failed because the subscription named is not valid for use by applications. (Reason Code 2523)

EventType.Description: The SelectionString of the subscriptions cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2524)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call was issued with the MQSO_ALTER option and the MQSD contained a SelectionString. It is not valid to alter the SelectionString of a subscription. (Reason Code 2524)

EventType.Description: The destination class of the subscriptions cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2533)
EventType.Explanation: An MQSUB call using option MQSO_ALTER was made changing the destination class of the subscription. The destination class of a subscription cannot be changed. (Reason Code 2533)

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source received Message Number Rollover Fault
EventType.Explanation: WS-ReliableMessaging RM Source received a Sequence Number Rollover SOAP Fault. The RM Source will transition to Closing state, and will send a CloseSequence to the RM Destination. No more messages will be sent on this RM Source Sequence, but acknowledgement and retransmission will complete.

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source received Create Sequence Refused Fault
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging Source sent a CreateSequence request to the noted endpoint, and it returned a CreateSequence Refused SOAP Fault. The RM Source will not be created, and the transaction causing the CreateSequence will fault out.

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source received Sequence Closed Fault
EventType.Explanation: WS-ReliableMessaging RM Source received a Sequence Closed SOAP Fault. This indicates that the RM Destination received a sequenced data or WS-RM control SOAP message, but that RM Destination was in Closed state. The RM Source will transition to Closed state. No more messages will be sent on this RM Source Sequence, but acknowledgement and retransmission will complete.

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source CreateSequence refused due to unsupported UsesSequenceSSL
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging Source sent a CreateSequence request to the noted endpoint, and it returned a MustUnderstand SOAP fault concerning the UsesSequenceSSL header. This indicates that SSL Session binding has been selected for security configuration in this gateway, but that the peer does not support this feature. The reason is the text from the SOAP fault. The RM Source will not be created, and the transaction causing the CreateSequence will fault out.
A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received by a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but the processing of incoming CreateSequence requests has been disabled by configuration.
A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received by a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there are already too many RM Destination Sequences on this object.
A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received on a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there was no AcksTo. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM CreateSequence rejected, Offer without Identifier
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received on a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there was an Offer element without an Identifier element within it. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM CreateSequence rejected, Offer without Endpoint
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received on a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there was an Offer element without an Endpoint element within it. A SOAP fault will be generated.
A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received on a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there was an Expires element containing a negative duration. A SOAP fault will be generated.

A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received on a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but there was an Expires element containing a duration that was not in conformance with the XML Schema for a Duration. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received for an unknown sequence
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an Identifier XML element that does not correpsond with any known sequence at an RM Destination in this gateway. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received for a closed sequence
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an Identifier XML element for a sequence in an RM Destination in this gateway that is in the Closed state. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received for a terminating sequence
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an Identifier XML element for a sequence in an RM Destination in this gateway that is in the Terminating state. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received with too high a sequence number
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an wsrm:Sequence SOAP header XML element, where the wsrm:MessageNumber element had a value greater than 9223372036854775807. No change is made to the state of the RM Destination, but the SOAP Body will not be processed. A SOAP fault will be generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received with an invalid acknowledgement
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an wsrm:SequenceAcknowledgement SOAP header XML element, where the wsrm:AcknowledgementRange elements have overlapping bounds, or where there is an invalid combination of the mutually exclusive wsrm:AcknowledgmentRange, wsrm:None, and wsrm:Nack elements. The acknowledgment will be ignored, but the rest of the message will be processed normally.

EventType.Description: SOAP message was received without required WS-RM header
EventType.Explanation: A SOAP message was received on a gateway that was configured to require the use of WS-RM, and it did not have a wsrm:Sequence header identifying it as being part of a WS-RM Sequence, and it was not a WS-RM control SOAP call. The message is dropped, and a SOAP Fault generated.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message received with a message number that is not InOrder
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an wsrm:Sequence SOAP header XML element, where the wsrm:MessageNumber element has a sequence number that is not one greater than the highest MessageNumber already recieved, and InOrder delivery assurance is in operation. Processing of the message will be delayed until the previous missing messages are received.

EventType.Description: WS-RM outgoing CreateSequence canceled, too many
EventType.Explanation: A message was being processed for which an RM Source should be created to the destination. However, the configured limit on the number of RM Sources for this gateway has been exceeded. The RM Source will not be created, and processing of the message will fail.

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source Seqeunce disabled for request processing
EventType.Explanation: A request is being processed, on a gateway with WS-RM enabled, but the creation of RM Source Sequences for request processing to the server has been disabled by configuration. The data message will be sent without WS-RM Sequencing.

EventType.Description: WS-RM Source Sequence disabled for response processing
EventType.Explanation: A response is being processed, on a gateway with WS-RM enabled, but the creation of RM Source Sequences for request processing to the client has been disabled by configuration. The data message will be sent without WS-RM Sequencing.

EventType.Description: WS-RM creating Source Sequence for data message
EventType.Explanation: A message is being processed, on a gateway with WS-RM enabled for output, and there is no existing RM Source to the destination Endpoint Reference of the message. One will be created, and transmission of this message will wait for creation to complete.

EventType.Description: WS-RM waiting to create Source Sequence for data message
EventType.Explanation: A message is being processed, on a gateway with WS-RM enabled for output, and there is a RM Source to the destination Endpoint Reference of the message, but it is still pending the CreateSequenceResponse from the RM Destination. Transmission of this message will wait for creation to complete.

A WS-ReliableMessaging CreateSequence message was received by a MultiProtocol Gateway or WS-Proxy, but the AcksTo Address is a WS-Address Endpoint Reference Address that represents "no such address", such as "http://www.w3.org/2005/08/addresing/none". A wsrm:CreateSequenceRefused SOAP fault is sent.

EventType.Description: WS-ReliableMessaging message received with out-of-range message number
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an message number too large to queue for inorder delivery. Increase the Destination maximum inorder queue length.

EventType.Description: WS-ReliableMessaging received too many out-of-order messages
EventType.Explanation: WS-ReliableMessaging received too many out-of-order messages. Increase the Destination Maximum Inorder Queue length or reduce the traffic rate.

EventType.Description: WS-RM message was received with a dupliate message number
EventType.Explanation: A WS-ReliableMessaging message was received having an wsrm:Sequence SOAP header XML element, where the wsrm:MessageNumber element was one that has already been received. The message will not be further processed, but a wsrm:SequenceAcknowledgement will probably be generated.
